<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="recruiting-process">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>comms</group>
    <domain>hr-recruiter</domain>
    <summary>Full-cycle talent acquisition framework: sourcing, JD writing, candidate personas, metrics, ATS optimization, offer management. Addresses pipeline bottlenecks from sourcing to close.</summary>
    <category>recruiting</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-25</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>recruiting</tag>
      <tag>full-cycle</tag>
      <tag>talent-acquisition</tag>
      <tag>sourcing</tag>
      <tag>hiring-process</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Recruiting Process (Full-Cycle)</title>
    <summary>A full-cycle talent acquisition framework covering ten methodologies from multi-channel sourcing through offer management. Each sub-methodology addresses a specific pipeline bottleneck: sourcing breadth, JD quality, candidate personas, passive outreach, ATS optimization, AI tooling, and metrics dashboards.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Full-cycle recruiting without a documented process devolves into reactive, channel-dependent hiring. Each gap in the pipeline (e.g., weak JD, over-reliance on job boards, no ATS automation) compounds: low application volume, poor screening signal, and slow offers pile up into long time-to-fill. Mapping each stage to a concrete sub-methodology makes bottlenecks addressable individually.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Building a sourcing strategy for a new role type or market.</item>
        <item>Diagnosing why a specific stage is underperforming (see recruitment-funnel-optimization for diagnosis).</item>
        <item>Designing or auditing a JD, ATS workflow, or candidate outreach sequence.</item>
        <item>Implementing metrics reporting for a recruiting function.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Executive search where a retained firm is running the process — overlap creates confusion.</item>
        <item>Single-hire, one-time role where building pipelines and personas is overhead, not value.</item>
        <item>Compliance-audit contexts — use retention-compliance methodology instead.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="multi-channel-sourcing">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use at least three sourcing channels per role; over-reliance on a single channel (e.g., job boards) caps the addressable candidate pool and biases toward active seekers.</statement>
        <rationale>LinkedIn data shows 70% of the global workforce is passively open to opportunities; job boards only reach active seekers, typically 30% of the market.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <section name="channel-selection-by-use-case">
        <p>LinkedIn: passive candidates, highest effort, highest yield for experienced roles. Employee referrals: culture-fit signal, lowest sourcing cost, fastest time-to-screen. Job boards: active seekers, medium effort, works for high-volume or well-known roles. University partnerships: entry-level pipeline, medium effort, requires relationship investment. Niche communities and Slack groups: specialized roles (e.g., ML engineers, security researchers). Agencies: hard-to-fill or time-sensitive roles; significant cost premium.</p>
      </section>
    </section>
    <section name="skills-based-hiring">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Remove degree requirements that are not job-essential; replace with skills assessments or portfolio evaluation.</statement>
        <rationale>76% of organizations report successful hires from candidates previously excluded by degree requirements (LinkedIn). Degree proxies exclude qualified candidates from under-resourced educational backgrounds without improving quality-of-hire.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Identify the 5-7 essential skills for the role (not proxies).</item>
        <item>Remove degree requirements that are not legally mandated.</item>
        <item>Create or source skills assessments tied to actual job tasks.</item>
        <item>Evaluate portfolio, open-source contributions, or past projects as evidence.</item>
        <item>Use structured interviews to assess skills not visible in the portfolio.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="passive-candidate-outreach">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Each outreach message must reference the candidate's specific work; generic "exciting opportunity" subject lines achieve less than 10% open rate.</statement>
        <rationale>Passive candidates receive multiple generic outreach messages weekly. A specific reference to a project, article, or contribution they produced proves the sender did research and respects their time.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Target response rate: 25-40%. Outreach structure: personalized subject (no "job opportunity"), opening referencing their specific work, value proposition framed for what they gain, low-commitment CTA (a conversation, not an application). Follow-up: 3 touches with different angles, then stop.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="talent-pipeline-building">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Build and maintain warm candidate lists for critical roles before those roles open; reactive hiring from a cold start adds 2-4 weeks to time-to-fill.</statement>
        <rationale>Pipeline building converts recruiting from a reactive sprint into an ongoing relationship. When a role opens, the first outreach goes to candidates who already know the company.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Identify 3-5 roles most likely to open in the next 2 quarters.</item>
        <item>Build a warm list of 20-50 candidates per role.</item>
        <item>Nurture with content, company updates, and event invitations — not job postings.</item>
        <item>Track engagement (opens, replies, event attendance).</item>
        <item>Activate the warm list within 24 hours of role opening.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="internal-mobility">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Post all roles internally before external sourcing begins; an internal hire closes 50-70% faster and retains institutional knowledge.</statement>
        <rationale>Internal candidates require less ramp time, already understand culture, and their move opens a backfill at a more junior level — cheaper to fill. Skipping internal posting destroys trust in career development commitments.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="job-description-writing">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Limit must-have requirements to 5-7 items and nice-to-have to 3-4; JDs listing 15+ requirements reduce qualified applicant volume without improving hire quality.</statement>
        <rationale>Research (LinkedIn, Textio) shows that long requirement lists disproportionately deter underrepresented candidates who self-screen out if they don't meet every requirement. Reducing to true requirements increases qualified applicant volume.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <section name="jd-structure">
        <p>Hook: why this role matters to the company and the market (2-3 sentences). Impact: what the hire will accomplish in the first year (concrete outcomes, not job duties). Requirements: 5-7 must-have skills or experiences, each grounded in actual job tasks. Nice-to-have: 3-4 bonus qualifications that differentiate candidates. Benefits: compensation range (required in many jurisdictions), equity, perks. Culture: team size, working style, decision-making norms.</p>
      </section>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Publishing a JD copied from a prior job posting without updating requirements to reflect the current role.</description>
        <reason>Stale JDs attract candidates for the previous role, not the current one. Misalignment surfaces in screening and wastes recruiter and candidate time.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="candidate-persona-development">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Define the target candidate persona before writing the JD or opening sourcing channels; without a profile, sourcing generates noise and screening becomes subjective.</statement>
        <rationale>A persona converts the hiring manager's vague "someone like our best performer" into specific, sourceable attributes: experience range, current role, motivations, channels. This makes sourcing targeted and screening criteria explicit.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <section name="persona-components">
        <p>Demographics: experience range (years), current title or adjacent titles, industries with transferable background. Motivations: what career goal does this role advance? What values must the company demonstrate? What are their deal-breakers (e.g., no remote, no equity)? Channels: where do they spend time online? How do they search for roles (referrals, LinkedIn, community)? What content do they consume? Messaging: what value proposition resonates (growth, mission, compensation, flexibility)? What objections must the JD or outreach preempt?</p>
      </section>
      <example type="good" title="Senior Software Engineer Persona">
        <note>5-8 years at Series B-C startup or scaleup. Motivated by technical autonomy and ownership. Searches via LinkedIn and engineering community newsletters. Objection: will we have greenfield work or inherit legacy code? Messaging: lead on new infra stack, no approval layers for architectural decisions.</note>
      </example>
      <p>Creating a persona template: Start by interviewing the hiring manager and top performer in the role. Identify their background (prior companies, title progression), skills hierarchy (what makes them succeed), and career goals that align with your role. Ask about their frustrations with previous employers and what motivated their moves. Document where they find roles, what content they consume, and what value propositions they respond to. Then reverse-engineer that profile: experience range, current industry, key technical skills, motivation drivers. Use the persona to inform sourcing channel selection, JD emphasis, and outreach messaging. A persona increases sourcing efficiency by 30-40% by reducing false-positive applications from candidates who don't match the profile.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="recruitment-metrics-dashboard">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Report six core metrics weekly or monthly; any metric without a defined target and owner degrades into a vanity number.</statement>
        <rationale>Metrics without targets drive reporting behavior, not improvement. Assigning ownership (recruiter for time-to-fill, compensation for offer acceptance) creates accountability.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <section name="core-metrics">
        <p>Time-to-fill: date hired minus date posted; target under 45 days; review weekly. Cost-per-hire: total recruiting cost divided by hires; target under $4,000; review monthly. Offer acceptance rate: accepts divided by offers extended; target above 85%; review weekly. Quality of hire: percentage meeting or exceeding expectations at 1-year review; target above 80%; review quarterly. Source effectiveness: application and hire volume by channel; review monthly. Candidate NPS: post-process survey; target above 50; measure continuously.</p>
      </section>
    </section>
    <section name="ats-optimization">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Application process must complete in under 5 minutes and render correctly on mobile; test with a real resume before publishing every role.</statement>
        <rationale>ATS default forms often include non-essential fields (graduation year, GPA, references before interview) that extend application time and reduce conversion. Mobile rendering issues silently drop applicants who don't self-report the problem.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <section name="ats-configuration-areas">
        <p>Application form: remove non-essential fields; keep under 10 required inputs; test on a mobile device. Resume parsing: validate with 10 real resumes from target pool; identify and correct misparse patterns. Automation: set up auto-acknowledgment within 24 hours; auto-reject only for hard knockout criteria. Communication: templatize rejection emails with enough specificity to not feel generic; automate scheduling prompts. Analytics: configure stage-by-stage conversion tracking for the funnel dashboard.</p>
      </section>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-recruiting-tools">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Audit every AI sourcing or screening tool for demographic bias before deployment; document the audit and review annually.</statement>
        <rationale>AI tools trained on historical hiring data replicate historical bias patterns. EEOC and EU AI Act require explainability for decisions affecting employment; undocumented AI use creates legal exposure.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <section name="tool-categories-and-use-cases">
        <p>AI sourcing: finds passive candidates matching a persona; high value for specialized roles. Resume screening: matches skills to JD; must be audited for false-negative rate by demographic. Chatbots: answer FAQs and schedule screens; frees recruiter time; do not use for evaluation decisions. Video interviewing: async first rounds for high-volume roles; ensure candidates with slow connections can rerecord. Skills assessments: validated, job-related tests; avoid general cognitive tests without validity data for the specific role.</p>
      </section>
    </section>
    <section name="offer-management">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Extend the offer within 48 hours of the hiring decision; every additional day increases competing-offer risk by a measurable margin.</statement>
        <rationale>Top candidates in active searches often have multiple processes running in parallel. A 5-day lag between decision and offer letter loses 20-30% of candidates in competitive markets.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <section name="offer-close-process">
        <p>Pre-offer: verbal commitment call from the hiring manager before the written offer; surface objections early while there is still room to address them. Offer call: personal call from hiring manager, not just an email; explains the offer and invites questions. Negotiation: know the band ceiling and what non-cash levers are available (signing bonus, extra PTO, equity refresh, start-date flexibility) before the call. Counter-offer handling: if the candidate signals a competing offer, ask what it would take to close; don't assume the competing package is better — often they prefer this role if the gap is small.</p>
      </section>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Sending the offer letter via email with no follow-up call and waiting for the candidate to respond.</description>
        <reason>An unaccompanied offer letter communicates low enthusiasm. Candidates who are on the fence read the absence of a personal call as a signal that the organization does not really want them.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
